# Path resolution: prefer `.cursor/` over `.github/` for agents, skills, rules

The gNB repository (typically mounted at `/workspace`) is migrating
shared AI assets from `.github/{agents,skills,rules,instructions,prompts}/`
to `.cursor/{agents,skills,rules}/`. During the transition many agent
files, skill files, `AGENTS.md` files, and subagent prompts still spell
their cross-references with the legacy `.github/` prefix while the
actual canonical copy now lives under `.cursor/`.

When you (the AI) encounter a path that starts with — or contains the
segment — `/.github/agents/`, `/.github/skills/`, `/.github/rules/`,
`/.github/instructions/`, or `/.github/prompts/` anywhere inside the
gNB workspace (markdown links, inline backticked paths, YAML front
matter, shell commands, subagent prompts you forward, etc.), resolve
the path with this two-step lookup:

1. Substitute `/.github/` with `/.cursor/` in the path and try to read /
   reference the resulting `.cursor/...` path first. If that file or
   directory exists, use it and silently treat the rewrite as the
   intended target.
2. Only if the rewritten `.cursor/...` path does not exist, fall back
   to the original `.github/...` path.

This rewrite applies **only to the five subdirectories listed above**
(shared AI assets). Do not rewrite unrelated `.github/` paths such as
`.github/workflows/`, `.github/CODEOWNERS`, `.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/`,
`.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`, or any other GitHub-platform file —
those remain authoritative under `.github/`.

When you delegate to a subagent and the prompt template you are about
to send contains a `.github/{agents|skills|rules|instructions|prompts}/`
path, rewrite it to `.cursor/...` first (after verifying the target
exists) before sending the prompt, so the subagent sees the canonical
location directly.

If both `.cursor/...` and `.github/...` exist and their contents
differ, prefer `.cursor/...` and note the divergence to the user — that
is a migration-cleanup signal, not a real conflict for path resolution.

This is a transitional rule. As authors migrate their references the
`.github/` form will disappear from new files; the rule should stay in
effect until the legacy copies are removed.
